Exploring Global Life Expectancy: A Study of Health and Demographic Factors¶

Team Members: Sawdah Munir and Saniya Nazeer

Summer 2024 Data Science Project¶

1. Introduction¶

As disease and health concerns are on the rise and continue to grow, we delve into the complexities of global health and demographic trend, using the data science lifecycle method. We will be exploring a wide range of quantitative factors ranging from economic indicators such as GDP, Total Expenditure to health metrics such as immunization coverage which comprises of diseases such as Polio, Hepatitis B, and more.

Throughout this project, we aim to answer how these factors can influence life expectancy. Through this, we would be equipped with the tools needed to predict future trends and be able to identify key factors.

This leads to why is this important? As we've all seen through the recent pandemic global health can be at a crisis at any moment. These insights are crucial as they can ultimately guide us and provide insight on which factors to prioritize in order to be able to improve overall health and life expectancy worldwide.

2. Data Curation¶

The dataset we are working with is from Kaggle, titled “Health and Demographics Dataset”. The set provides global data about life expectancy, health expenditure, and other public health information. For each entry, the country and year from which the data was recorded are present, allowing us to see trends over time as well as within geographic locations.

Link to the dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uom190346a/health-and-demographics-dataset

We start by observing the features within the dataset.

The description of the dataset provides insight into what units each feature utilizes, and how these numbers measure their designated feature.

Highlights of these descriptions include:

  • Life Expectancy - "The average number of years a person born in that year can expect to live"
  • Total Expenditure - "The total health expenditure as a percentage of the country's GDP"
    • The World Health Organization (WHO) explains more about the importance of this measurement here: https://www.who.int/data/nutrition/nlis/info/health-expenditure
  • Hepatitis, Polio, and Diphtheria are measured in rate of vaccination per 100 people to demonstrate the immunization coverage in that given year.
    • More info on Immunization Coverage from WHO: https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/immunization-coverage
  • Measles and HIV/AIDS are measured in rate of infected individual per 1000 people to demonstrate the prevalence of the disease.
  • Schooling is measured by the average number of years of schooling members of the population partake in

After cross-referencing the description of the dataset, we found that two column names had been swapped. We resolved this issue below. We also adjusted the formatting of several column names in order to make references easier as we continue to work with the data.

3. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Creating a Correlation Coefficient Matrix¶

Since we approached this data with the assumption of exploring the effect of different factors on a population's life expectancy, we first wanted to explore what correlations exist in the dataset at hand. To do this, we first created a Correlation Coefficient Matrix to highlight existing relationships.

In [8]:
# First, prepare a separate dataframe for manipulation
df_corr = (df.drop('Country', axis=1))
corr_matrix = df_corr.corr().to_numpy()

# Determine which correlations are significant
# In other words, coefficients with absolute values greater than 0.5
strengths = np.abs(df_corr.values) > 0.5
drops = []
sig_corrs = {} # Matrix storing significant correlation coefficients

# Filtering and storing significant coefficients
n = len(df_corr.columns)
for i in range(n):
  for j in range(n):
    if (strengths[i][j] == True) and (df_corr.columns[i] != df_corr.columns[j]):
      if not np.isin(j, drops):
        sig_corrs[corr_matrix[i][j]] = (df_corr.columns[i], df_corr.columns[j])
  drops.append(i)

# Sort remaining coefficients
sig_corrs = dict(sorted(sig_corrs.items()))

# Store positive coefficients separately
pos = {corr: pair for corr, pair in sig_corrs.items() if corr > 0}
pos = dict(sorted(sig_corrs.items(), reverse=True))
pos_list = list(pos.keys())

# Store negative coefficients
neg = {corr: pair for corr, pair in sig_corrs.items() if corr < 0}
neg_list = list(neg.keys())

Since both significant positive and significant negative correlations were considered, we consider these as different types of relationships. The scaling for determining level of correlation was done with absolute value where:

0.9 to 1.0 signifies a Very High Correlation

0.7 to 0.9 signifies a High Correlation

0.5 to 0.7 signifies a Moderate Correlation

Since the resulting dictionary of pairings with a correlation coefficient higher than 0.5 was rather large, for each of these categories, the top 3 values meeting each criteria were pulled.

Kruskal-Wallis Hypothesis Test¶

To decide how to explore what the dataset reveals about the role of immunization coverage on a population, we considered what else we were searching for in the data. Since we planned to both predict Life Expectancy based on financial factors, such as Total Expenditure and GDP, it made sense to consider how these factors are tied with immunization. Specifically, whether higher expenditure meant a larger immunization coverage across the country. Thus, the first hypothesis test we conducted explores the relationship between Total Expenditure and immunization coverage for Polio.

  • $H_{0}$: The amount of total health expenditure in a country does not have an effect on the population's immunization coverage for polio.
  • $H_{A}$: The amount of total health expenditure in a country has an effect on the population's immunization coverage for polio.

Alpha Value is 0.05

When approaching this test, we wanted to categorize the total expenditure into ranges of spending. This was a more practical approach to communicating the results of the testing, as we wanted to be able to identify the effect of different brackets of health expenditure, rather than a singular value.

We at first wanted to conduct an ANOVA test, but as seen below, the mean spending is quite low in comparison to the range of possible values, with a very large standard deviation. This raised concern about whether the data was normally distributed. When plotted as a histogram, we can see that the data is extremely positively skewed, and thus does not meet the assumptions of normality required for an ANOVA test. Thus, we chose to conduct a Kruskal-Wallis Test instead.

In [12]:
def categorize(val):
  if val <= 5000:
    return 'Low'
  elif val <= 10000:
    return 'Mid'
  elif val <= 15000:
    return 'High'
  else:
    return 'Very High'

df_kruskal = pd.DataFrame(df)
df_kruskal['Bracket'] = df_kruskal['Total Expenditure'].apply(lambda x: categorize(x))
kruskal_ct = pd.crosstab(df_kruskal['Bracket'], df_kruskal['Polio'], rownames='B')
brackets = kruskal_ct.columns
pvalue = scipy.stats.kruskal(kruskal_ct[brackets].loc['Low'], kruskal_ct[brackets].loc['Mid'],
                           kruskal_ct[brackets].loc['High'], kruskal_ct[brackets].loc['Very High']).pvalue
print("P-Value: " + str(pvalue))

P-Value: 3.6410367835425685e-43

Since the P-value of $3.641 \times 10^{-43}$ is well below the alpha value of 0.05, there is an extremely low probability the null hypothesis is true. This suggests that the total health expenditure per capita of a country has an effect on its population's immunization coverage for polio.

Taking note of the scatter plot as well, it is also important to note how sample size may be affecting the test's results. Even with the use of a non-parametric test like the Kruskal-Wallis test, it seems that the extreme skew of the data is still affecting the ability to determine a confident result. With the "Low" bracket being the largest, it appears that there is a wider range of values to account for than in other categories. It may be helpful to reconsider the criteria for each bracket, as well as evaluating immunization coverage for other diseases.

Mann-Whitney U Hypothesis Test¶

Beyond life expectancy we explore infant deaths and investigate whether there is any significant difference in infant deaths between developed and developing countries. This will further allow us to have a better understanding of there truly is a disparity between developed and developing countries and if there might be underlying factors worth exploring.

  • $H_{0}$ (Null Hypothesis): There is no difference in infant deaths between developed and developing countries (infant deaths are the same).

  • $H_{A}$ (Alternative Hypothesis): There is a difference in infant deaths between developed and developing countries.

Alpha Value is 0.05

alpha = 0.05
statistic, p_value = scipy.stats.mannwhitneyu(developed, developing)

print(f'Mann-Whitney U Test Statistic: {statistic:.3f}')
print(f'P-value: {p_value}')

if p_value < alpha:
    print("Since the p_value is less than alpha we reject the null hypothesis that there is no significant difference in infant deaths between developed and developing countries.")
else:
    print("Since the p_value is greater than alpha we fail to reject the null hypothesis that there is no significant difference in infant deaths between developed and developing countries.")

4. Primary Analysis¶

Predicting Life Expectancy Using Average Years of Schooling¶

Since the correlation coefficient matrix calculated suggested a high positive correlation between Life Expectancy and Schooling, we decided to build a model that would predict Life Expectancy based on the average number of years of schooling. The World Health Organization (WHO) discusses the importance of female education levels as a factor impacting life expectancy and quality of life. While our dataset is not able to specify by gender, we found various other studies exploring the impact of schooling on life expectancy, and wanted to explore the general relationship in this dataset. Given our exploration in other sections about financial impact on life expectancy and health, schooling was another relevant factor to explore.

We started by creating a linear regression model as a baseline for determining an accurate model for prediction.

In [18]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression, LogisticRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet
import math

seed = 24

# Splitting into training and test sets to help determine model accuracy later
split_df = train_test_split(df, test_size=0.3, random_state=seed)

X_disease_train = split_df[0][['Schooling']]
X_disease_test = split_df[1][['Schooling']]
y_disease_train = split_df[0][['Life Expectancy']]
y_disease_test = split_df[1][['Life Expectancy']]

model_disease = LinearRegression().fit(X_disease_train, y_disease_train)
y_disease_pred = pd.DataFrame(model_disease.predict(X_disease_test))

# Calculate Mean Squared Error and R-Squared Value to observe model accuracy
mse = mean_squared_error(y_disease_test, y_disease_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_disease_test, y_disease_pred)

print("Root Mean Squared Error: " + str(math.sqrt(mse)) + " R-Squared Value: " + str(r2))

Root Mean Squared Error: 5.729241815784378 R-Squared Value: 0.5651642065036828

After training the model with a portion of the data, we then used a separate portion to test its ability to accurately predict Life Expectancy based on the given average number of Schooling. When comparing these predicted values to the actual values, we can see that there is an root mean squared error of about 5.729. This means that the model's prediction for Life Expectancy deviates from the true values by about 5.729 years on average. The R-Squared value also reflects the model's moderate ability to make accurate predictions, since at 0.565 it is closer to 1, than 0. This indicates a moderate ability to account for the variance present in the dataset.

Given that there was room for the unaltered linear regression model to better predict values, we then treated the relationship between Life Expectancy and Schooling as non-linear. Thus, for our next version of the regression model, we first transformed the data so that the relationship between variables would be linear before being fed into the linear regression model. For this transformation, we chose a degree of 4, in order to accommodate the non-linear relationship without overfitting to the training data. A larger degree would allow the regression line to match the relationship more closely; however, it also would run the risk of being so attune to the training data that it is unable to predict values for new, unfamiliar data.

In [19]:
model_disease_poly = make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(4), LinearRegression()).fit(X_disease_train, y_disease_train)
y_disease_poly_pred = pd.DataFrame(model_disease_poly.predict(X_disease_test))

mse = mean_squared_error(y_disease_test, y_disease_poly_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_disease_test, y_disease_poly_pred)

print("Root Mean Squared Error: " + str(math.sqrt(mse)) + " R-Squared Value: " + str(r2))

Root Mean Squared Error: 5.566757834379124 R-Squared Value: 0.5894787545959688

Here, we can see marginal improvement. The root mean squared error decreased by about .16, while the R-Squared value increased by about .02. While both these changes show improvement, it is not large enough to argue that the polynomial regression is an improvement from the linear regression model. Since the correlation coefficient was about .728, this value indicates a rather high positive correlation. The data types for both Life Expectancy and Schooling are continuous, raising the question of what might be a preferable method than Linear Regression to model and predict the relationship between these two variables. It may be necessary to consider a different method, or continue to transform or regularize the data to form an improved model.

Predicting Life Expectancy Based On Economics (Income Composition of Resources)¶

Based on the exploratory section, we have seen a high correlation between life expectancy and income composition of resouces through the heatmap in the correlation coefficient matrix. Furthermore, through the analysis of historical trends of life expectancy, we uncovered the differences between developed and developing countries and that high life expectancies in developed countries could potentially translate to economic factors. Therefore, here we are creating a linear regression model due to the quantitative nature of the data and predicting life expectancy based on Income Composition of Resources.

In [20]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

# Defining X and y
X_econ = df[['Income composition of resources']]  # Independent variable
y_econ = df['Life Expectancy']  # Dependent variable

random_state = 42
np.random.seed(random_state)

# Splitting the data into training and testing sets
X_econ_train, X_econ_test, y_econ_train, y_econ_test = train_test_split(X_econ, y_econ, random_state=42)


# Creating a Linear Regression model
model_econ = LinearRegression()

# Fit the model
model_econ.fit(X_econ_train, y_econ_train)

# predicting
y_econ_pred = model_econ.predict(X_econ_test)

# Evaluation of the model
mse = mean_squared_error(y_econ_test, y_econ_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_econ_test, y_econ_pred)

print("Mean Squared Error:", mse)
print("R-Squared Value:", r2)

Mean Squared Error: 30.12199627870841
R-Squared Value: 0.5973405107278367

Through the evaluation of the model, we see that our model is a moderate (leaning on the stronger side) fit to the data. This is because the R^2 coeffcient is approximately 0.597 which is in between 0 and 1 but leaning more to 1. And as we know the closer the coefficient is to a 1, the model cpatures more of the variance/complexities in the data. Also, we know there's some error (average squared difference between predicted and actual values) and the closer it is to 0 the better here.

It would be beneficial to explore the possibility that there is a non linear relationship within the data. In this case, it would be better to use polynomial features to transform the assumed non linear relationship into a linear one. This could allow for an effective application of linear regression. Reasoning behind this is because the R^2 coefficient is not exactly super close to 1 and getting a lower MSE value would indicate less error.

In [21]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

degree = 3

# Creating a pipeline with Polynomial Regression
econ_poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2)

model_econ_poly = make_pipeline(econ_poly, LinearRegression())

# fit
model_econ_poly.fit(X_econ_train, y_econ_train)

# predict
y_econ_pred_poly = model_econ_poly.predict(X_econ_test)

# Evaluation of the model
test_r2 = r2_score(y_econ_test, y_econ_pred_poly)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_econ_test, y_econ_pred_poly)
print(f'Test MSE (Polynomial Regression): {mse}')
print(f'Test R-squared (Polynomial Regression): {test_r2}')

Test MSE (Polynomial Regression): 23.034189564118908
Test R-squared (Polynomial Regression): 0.6920876385526196

Compared to our previous linear regression model, we see a significant improvement in our Polynomial Regression one through both the MSE and R^2 coefficient. As we see our MSE has decreased from 30 to 23 approximately indicating less error overall. Also our R^2 has increased and is closer to 1. This indicates a better capture of variance and better fit of model to the data.

6. Insights and Conclusion¶

After progressing through this project, it is clear that there is much more to be explored in the realm of relationships between Life Expectancy and different health statistics for a country's public health. We were able to scratch the surface regarding potential influences, such as average years of schooling for a population. While we separately delved into how a year's worth of health expenditure may affect a country's immunization coverage for a disease within said year, further exploration would benefit from taking one step further to factoring in life expectancy.

The results of our linear regression model continued to indicate the potential for how interconnected the features of this dataset may be. Despite the moderately high positive correlation between schooling and life expectancy, there was still a significant margin of error in being able to accurately predict life expectancy. In a broader context, we can understand how difficult it may be to pinpoint exact solutions to issues of health disparity within a population. By using life expectancy as a representative of this disparity, we were able to learn the obstacles in adequately addressing precise influences and what changes may create positive change to increase life expectancy.

An unfamiliar reader would be able to use this project to ease into the complexities of identifying relationships between variables relating to a country's health. Throughout the process of exploration and analysis, we are able to take different avenues into addressing this issue. While there was a lot of trial and error, we discovered the potential for important relationships and were able to identify areas a more detailed project would be able to address. As the UN's 2022 Policy Brief on inequalities in life expectancy states, "countries do not systematically monitor inequalities in life expectancy, suggesting that their importance is still unknown or less understood by policymakers". This demonstrates the room for exploration in this topic and the importance of exploring various possible relationships.

An important takeaway from this project as seen through exploring historical life expectancy trends, infant mortality for developed vs. developing countries, correlation between economic factors and life expectancy, and the model which predicted life expectancy based on economic factors. It is clear that there is a huge disparity when it comes to developed and developing countries. Generally, developed countries tend to enjoy a higher life expectancies due to various economic advantages.This calls for a crucial need in economic resources in these developing countries so that they can achieve high life expectancies as well and overall better health.
